                "href": "/profile/James-Hall-234"
            },
            "answer_text": "For the US army the official answer is \u201cNo\" But this can change depending on the circumstances. Explosives are always a \u201chell no\" because a boobytrapped RPG is just as bad as it sounds. However some units will officially confiscate small arms when found in enemy supply dumps, depending on what is feasable under operational conditions. These arn't for soldiers to keep, but for a kind of data mining. Serialized weapons are semi traceable. DIfferent kinds of arms can indicate different trading partners. Type and supplier of ammo used is a good indicator of who gets what and from where. Also, if you find a weapon, it is kind of stupid to leave it for anyone else, including a kid, to come by and pick up. Usually these weapons are disposed of in various ways, or kept by intelligence groups. Mostly the former and not so much the latter. One common disposal method is either blowing them up with the weekly or monthly ordinance disposal or using a metal chop saw to render them worthless and scrapping them. Sometimes they will be redistributed to allied groups of locals in the area if the relstionship is particularly high. ",
